-- Japan, India, Malaysia, South Korea, Thailand: Asia Bond, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-06-28T22:24:47Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-28/japan-india-malaysia-south-korea-thailand-asia-bond-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: The government will report the jobless rate and
industrial production for May. The unemployment rate declined to
5 percent from 5.1 percent in April, according to the median
estimate of economists before the statistics bureau reports the
data at 8:30 a.m. in Tokyo. Factory output was unchanged last
month after rising 1.3 percent in April, according to another
Bloomberg survey before the Ministry of Economy, Trade and
Industry releases the numbers at 8:50 a.m.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.15 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 89.35 per dollar at 7:23 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 India: The central bank will report tomorrow the nation’s
balance of payments for the three months ended March 31. India’s
current-account shortfall probably shrank to $5.75 billion last
quarter from $12.03 billion in the previous three months,
according to the median estimate of economists in a Bloomberg
News survey.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.59
percent. The rupee was at 46.21.  
 Malaysia: The government plans to raise as much as 3
billion ringgit ($930 million) selling three-year bonds.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent debt maturing in November
2019 was 3.96 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit
was at 3.2235.  
 South Korea: The central bank will report on the nation’s
current-account balance in May. South Korea had a current-
account surplus of $1.49 billion in April.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.51 percent. The won was at 1,201.30.  
 Thailand: The government plans to auction as much as 3
billion baht ($93 million) of bonds maturing in 2040. In
addition the central bank will offer 15 billion baht each of 90-
and 181-day bills and 20 billion baht of 27-day debt.  
 The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in June 2019
was 3.18 percent. The baht was at 32.38.  
